II 47 hanc virtutem vestram. It is apparently colloquial usage and therefore not unsuited to a conversational or epistolary style. Cicero has but one instance in the speeches (pro Lig. 35 hi tui). In Quint. it is very rare (e. g. I 3, 3 hic meus) but in Pliny’s letters, as we are not surprised to observe, it is correspondingly frequent.

2 frequens et adsidua: John well remarks that the interposition of ‘nobis' strongly favors the predicative meaning of these words rather than the usual interpretation which regards them as one of the very numerous instances of fullness or redundancy of expres- sion in the D. This view is also in a measure confirmed by Cicero who (pro Planc. 8 ext.) has the phrase ‘adsidua frequentia.’ ‘To dispute repeatedly and. earnestly has almost become a habit with us.'
